es, factories, tenement houses, and fiercely defended ethnic neighborhoods into a truly global urban center. Reinterpreting the familiar narrative that Chicago’s autocratic machine politics shaped its institutions and public life, Andrew J. Diamond demonstrates how the grassroots politics of race crippled progressive forces and enabled an alliance of downtown business interests to promote a neoliberal agenda that created stark inequalities. Chicago on the Make takes the story into the twenty-first century, chronicling Chicago’s deeply entrenched social and urban problems as the city ascended to the national stage during the Obama years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aamerican racism.  aanthropologists.  achicago historian.  achicago illinois.  acity planning.  aclass warfare.  afamous city.  agrassroots politics.  aillinois historians.  ajournalism.  anational stage.  aobama administration.  aohare.  apublishing.  arace equality.  asegregation in america.  aurban planning.  aurban problems.  awindy city.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028648140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096171540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961715423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961715/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles